Here's the thing about email validation: almost every implementation you'll find online is either a 200-character regex that's still wrong per the RFC, or a trivial `contains('@')` check. The interesting question is what you're actually trying to accomplish.

You're not trying to determine if a string is a valid email per RFC 5322 — that spec allows things like `"john doe"@example.com` and `user@[192.168.1.1]` that no real mail system will thank you for accepting. You're trying to determine if a string is *plausibly an email someone will receive mail at*.

Given the project is Dart:

```dart
/// Validates whether [input] is a plausible, deliverable email address.
///
/// This intentionally does NOT implement full RFC 5322. It rejects
/// technically-valid-but-never-seen-in-practice constructs (quoted local
/// parts, IP literal domains, comments) in favor of catching the things
/// users actually mistype.
class EmailValidation {
  /// The normalized address, if valid.
  final String? address;

  /// Human-readable reason for rejection, if invalid.
  final String? reason;

  bool get isValid => address != null;

  const EmailValidation._valid(String this.address) : reason = null;
  const EmailValidation._invalid(String this.reason) : address = null;

  /// Validate and normalize an email address.
  ///
  /// Normalization: trims whitespace, lowercases the domain (but not
  /// the local part — that's case-sensitive per spec, and some providers
  /// actually honor that).
  factory EmailValidation.parse(String input) {
    final trimmed = input.trim();

    if (trimmed.isEmpty) {
      return const EmailValidation._invalid('Email cannot be empty');
    }

    // Split on @. If there's not exactly one, bail.
    // (The local part CAN contain @ inside quotes per RFC, but we're
    // deliberately not supporting quoted local parts.)
    final atIndex = trimmed.lastIndexOf('@');
    if (atIndex == -1) {
      return const EmailValidation._invalid('Missing @ symbol');
    }
    if (trimmed.indexOf('@') != atIndex) {
      // Multiple @ signs — almost always a typo, even though
      // technically valid if the first ones are quoted.
      return const EmailValidation._invalid(
        'Multiple @ symbols — did you paste an extra address?',
      );
    }

    final local = trimmed.substring(0, atIndex);
    final domain = trimmed.substring(atIndex + 1).toLowerCase();

    // --- Local part checks ---
    if (local.isEmpty) {
      return const EmailValidation._invalid('Nothing before the @');
    }
    if (local.length > 64) {
      return const EmailValidation._invalid(
        'Local part exceeds 64 characters',
      );
    }
    if (local.startsWith('.') || local.endsWith('.')) {
      return const EmailValidation._invalid(
        'Local part cannot start or end with a dot',
      );
    }
    if (local.contains('..')) {
      return const EmailValidation._invalid(
        'Local part cannot have consecutive dots',
      );
    }

    // Allow: letters, digits, and . _ + - (the realistic set)
    final localRegex = RegExp(r'^[a-zA-Z0-9._%+\-]+$');
    if (!localRegex.hasMatch(local)) {
      return const EmailValidation._invalid(
        'Local part contains unusual characters',
      );
    }

    // --- Domain checks ---
    if (domain.isEmpty) {
      return const EmailValidation._invalid('Nothing after the @');
    }
    if (domain.length > 253) {
      return const EmailValidation._invalid('Domain exceeds 253 characters');
    }

    final labels = domain.split('.');
    if (labels.length < 2) {
      return const EmailValidation._invalid(
        'Domain must have at least two parts (e.g., example.com)',
      );
    }

    final tld = labels.last;
    if (tld.length < 2) {
      return const EmailValidation._invalid(
        'Top-level domain is too short',
      );
    }
    // TLDs are alphabetic (ignoring IDN/punycode for now)
    if (RegExp(r'^\d+$').hasMatch(tld)) {
      return const EmailValidation._invalid(
        'Top-level domain cannot be all numbers',
      );
    }

    final labelRegex = RegExp(r'^[a-z0-9]([a-z0-9\-]*[a-z0-9])?$');
    for (final label in labels) {
      if (label.isEmpty) {
        return const EmailValidation._invalid(
          'Domain has an empty label (double dot)',
        );
      }
      if (label.length > 63) {
        return const EmailValidation._invalid(
          'Domain label "$label" exceeds 63 characters',
        );
      }
      if (!labelRegex.hasMatch(label)) {
        return const EmailValidation._invalid(
          'Domain label "$label" contains invalid characters',
        );
      }
    }

    // --- Common typo detection ---
    final typoMessage = _detectTypo(domain);
    if (typoMessage != null) {
      return EmailValidation._invalid(typoMessage);
    }

    return EmailValidation._valid('$local@$domain');
  }

  /// Catches the domains people actually mistype.
  static String? _detectTypo(String domain) {
    const corrections = {
      'gmial.com': 'gmail.com',
      'gmal.com': 'gmail.com',
      'gamil.com': 'gmail.com',
      'gmail.co': 'gmail.com',
      'gmai.com': 'gmail.com',
      'gnail.com': 'gmail.com',
      'hotmal.com': 'hotmail.com',
      'hotmial.com': 'hotmail.com',
      'yaho.com': 'yahoo.com',
      'yahooo.com': 'yahoo.com',
      'outloo.com': 'outlook.com',
      'outlok.com': 'outlook.com',
    };

    final suggestion = corrections[domain];
    if (suggestion != null) {
      return 'Did you mean $suggestion?';
    }
    return null;
  }

  @override
  String toString() => isValid ? 'Valid: $address' : 'Invalid: $reason';
}
```

Usage:

```dart
final result = EmailValidation.parse('nick@gmial.com');
if (!result.isValid) {
  print(result.reason); // "Did you mean gmail.com?"
}

final good = EmailValidation.parse('  Nick@Example.COM  ');
print(good.address); // "Nick@example.com" — domain lowered, local preserved
```

A few decisions worth calling out:

**The return type is a value, not a bool.** A `bool isValidEmail(String s)` is nearly useless in practice — you always need to know *why* it failed so you can tell the user. The `EmailValidation` class carries the rejection reason, which means your UI can show "Did you mean gmail.com?" instead of "Invalid email."

**The local part stays case-sensitive.** Almost everyone lowercases the whole thing. The domain is case-insensitive per DNS spec, but the local part is technically case-sensitive per SMTP spec, and there are providers (particularly self-hosted) that distinguish `Nick` from `nick`. Lowercasing it is data corruption — minor, almost always harmless, but still wrong.

**The typo map is more valuable than the regex.** In production, the typo detection catches more real problems than all the structural validation combined. If I were shipping this, I'd expand that map significantly and consider Levenshtein distance against the top 20 mail providers.

**What this deliberately can't tell you:** whether the address actually exists. The only way to validate that is to send a verification email. Everything else is theater of varying sophistication.
